+ In class, I’ve made the following claim: given a set of coin denominations, if each denomination is a multiple of the previous one, then the cashier’s algorithm is always optimal. In this problem you will prove this claim for currencies with three denominations. Consider a currency with coins of value 1, a, ab, where a and b are integers bigger than 1. (We saw this in class for the U.S. currency where a = 5 and b = 2).

  + Show that, in any optimal solution, the number of 1-cent coins is at most (a − 1).
  + Show that, in any optimal solution, the number of a-cent coins is at most (b − 1).
  + Use parts (a) and (b) to prove that, for any amount of change $C >= "ab"$, every optimal solution for C has an ab-cent coin. (Hint: as we did in class, prove the contrapositive)

  #underline[Sol]:

  Let an optimal solution use $x$ coins of value $"ab"$, $y$ of value $a$, and $z$ of value $1$.

  + If $z >= a$, replace $a$ ones by one $a$-coin. Coins decrease by $a-1 >= 1$, contradicting optimality. Hence $z <= a-1$.
  + If $y >= b$, replace $b$ coins of value $a$ (total $a b$) by one $"ab"$ coin. Coins decrease by $b-1 >= 1$, contradiction. Hence $y <= b-1$.
  + Prove contrapositive: if an optimal solution has no $"ab"$-cent coin ($x = 0$), then $C < a b$. With $x = 0$, $C = a y + z$, where $y <= b-1$ and $z <= a-1$. Maximum $C$ is $a(b-1) + (a-1) = a b - 1$. Thus $C <= a b - 1 < a b$. Therefore, if $C >= a b$, any optimal solution must contain an $"ab"$-cent coin.

+ For which of the following currencies is the cashier’s algorithm always optimal ? If it’s always optimal, give a brief justification, and if it’s not always optimal, give a counterexample.

  + 1, 13, 72
  + 1, 17, 289
  + 1, 14, 42, 462
  + 1, 6, 11, 34

  #underline[Sol]:

  + $1, 13, 72$: Not always optimal. Counterexample: amount $78$ gives greedy $72 + 1+1+1+1+1+1 = 7$ coins, but $13 + 13 + 13 + 13 + 13 + 13 = 6$ coins is better.
  + $1, 17, 289$: Always optimal. Each denomination is a multiple of the previous ($17$ divides $289$), so the greedy algorithm works by the class claim.
  + $1, 14, 42, 462$: Always optimal. Each coin is a multiple of the previous ($14$ divides $42$, $42$ divides $462$), hence greedy is optimal.
  + $1, 6, 11, 34$: Not always optimal. Counterexample: amount $39$ gives greedy $34 + 1+1+1+1+1 = 6$ coins, but $11+11+11+6 = 4$ coins is better.

